The design aimed to balance for degree of change but this seems to have gone wrong for some signs due to errors with the experiment versions. This may complicate things a bit since this means that the design is PARTIALLY within items and PARTIALLY between items. However, most items are counterbalanced .

Creating tibbles

For the prime accuracy analysis, we just need to reduce the tibble to primes only:

vpAccPrimes <- filter(vp, PrimeTarget == 'prime')
summary(vpAccPrimes$PrimeTarget)
##          practice    prime   target 
##        0        0    10215        0

The prime accuracy analysis will be conducted on 10215 trials

For the prime RT analysis, well additionally exclude incorrect responses and outlying trials (M+2SD) :

vpRTPrimes <- filter(vpAccPrimes, ExclIncorrect != 1) %>% filter(ExclSlow != 1)
summary(vpRTPrimes$PrimeTarget)
##          practice    prime   target 
##        0        0     8900        0

The prime accuracy analysis will be conducted on 8900 trials

For the Accuracy difference analysis, well exclude prime-target pairs that do not neatly fit into the three difficulty categories. Firstly those pairs with a 135 rotation (e.g.90L-45R; 54 pairs total = 0.53% of data); as well as pairs with a 90-opposite rotation (e.g.45L-45R; 1383 pairs total = 13.54% of data - quite a lot unfortunately!)

vpAccTargets <- filter(vp, Excl135Deg != 1) %>% filter(ExclOpposite !=1) %>%  
                    filter(PrimeTarget == 'target')
summary(vpAccTargets$PrimeTarget)
##          practice    prime   target 
##        0        0        0     8865

The accuracy difference analysis will be conducted on 8865 prime-target pairs

For the RT difference analysis, well additionally exclude incorrect trials (and their pairs), as well as the 877 fast/slow trials (and their 877 pairs):. This is because we cannot calculate difference scores when one trial of a prime-target pair has been excluded, meaning its pair must be excluded too.

Side angles seems to cause fewer problems for accuracy to one-handed signs. Accuracy is actually higher at 0 for 2Hs and 2HD, and drops more as angle increases, where one hand may begin to occlude the other. For accuracy, again there is less variation cause by angle for 1H signs. 2HD signs are slowest of all sign types at 0, and angle is again disruptive. However, 2Hs signs start fastest at 0 and see huge slowdowns as angle increases likely due to occlusion. (Running this again based on just the prime data alone has removed a lot of priming-related noise and shows much clearer patterns that are very interesting!)
